<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/swccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> You And What Army??<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.60)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=1625'>Derek "UnknownGlyph" Tessier</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=1625&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> April 10, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Quite often when you read a tournament report you see the phrase “got the swarm out, GAME OVER”.  It seems that when a swarm is sent out it comes back victorious.  I’ve puzzled over this and found some counters to swarms that could quite possibly fit into any deck type.<br>
<br>
I’d like to define the term swarm so that you and I see eye to eye.  A swarm is any time where the number of minions is larger than the number of companions.  A successful swarm is one where the stacking of “extra” minions results in guaranteed damage to a companion or even better an overwhelming of the ring-bearer (most common) or other character (sometimes necessary).  Swarms can be achieved by any shadow culture but of course Moria is most consistent in pulling it off.<br>
<br>
With this simple definition of swarm we’re off to be heros and live up to the saying “you and what army?”<br>
<br>
Alright, let’s look at what allows a swarm to “become”.<br>
1) Twilight, unless it’s Moria and condition city your opponent needs a lot of twilight.<br>
2) Conditions, this is more based on Moria.  Most Moria swarm decks require mass amounts of conditions to pull of swarms often and consistently.<br>
3) Unlimited minions: in hand or accessible from other sources.  Such as retrieving from discard (ie. Tol Brandir pulling trackers) or from active conditions (ie. Goblin Swarms).<br>
4) Fellowship size dictates ease of swarm creation.  Larger fellowships are harder to swarm.<br>
5) I’m stronger than you are, minions overwhelm companions.<br>
<br>
Now that we know what constitutes a swarm and what is required to create a swarm let’s find out how to prevent the devastating damage resulting from a swarm.  We’ll go through each of the five requirements of a swarm and lay out the preventative “medicine” for each.<br>
<br>
1) Preventing the Twilight.<br>
Now, this style of anti-swarm is very theme related.  Achieving twilight denial can be done any number of ways.  Most popular are the ranger / no stranger to shadow combo and the Hobbit / a talent for not being seen combo.  Both of these are not very viable in decks that don’t play 2+ Hobbits or maintain a ranger only fellowship.  Another way to reduce twilight is with the use of glamdring and sting.  Now sting can be played in every deck, since all decks have to play Frodo.  Problems occur with this because a) you’re exerting Frodo thereby weakening him, and b) it’s only successful against Orc based shadow decks.  Glamdring is less useful since you must play Gandalf to use it, this thereby eliminates it from many decks themes.  Gimli MOM version provides a choke underground but swarms are more likely occurring at sites 7-9 so his ability is quite limited.  There are a few other ways to limit twilight but those are more based in double move scenarios since the twilight reduction from these sources occurs during the regroup phase ie Able guide.  Overall, preventing twilight has a limited success, since Moria decks can get around low twilight with their massive twilight adding abilities.  Also denial style of deck is condition heavy so shadow condition removal tactics reduce your twilight denial thereby forcing you to suck up a swarm.  But this style is also very useful in preventing deployment of minions *period*.  So, using it won’t harm you if a non-swarm deck is played.<br>
<br>
2) Condition Removal.<br>
Well, basically this really only stops the Moria swarm from becoming abusive.  Keeping the twilight adding loops of Moria down to a minimum is very handy.  Currently, I believe only 3 cultures can take out shadow conditions from the support area.  Elves, Gandalf and Shire cultures have this ability.  Many decks rely on one of these cultures so this prevention of the Moria swarm is very doable.  Now this does little in preventing a straight out mass deploy of minions by any culture so it lacks any direct effect on a good draw and a mass of twilight.  It is also good to note that condition removal has added benefits to the game so splashing some removal isn’t wasting space in your deck because there are many other conditions which can harm your fellowship.<br>
<br>
3) Denying them minions.<br>
This section only looks at how to prevent the shadow from having access to minions not preventing deployment of them.  For starters, Moria has stacking condition which allow a nice supply of minions.  Condition removal takes care of this.  Other cultures have the ability of “raising the dead”.  Such as Uruk Captain, Ulaire Nertea, Tol Brandir etc.  Preventing these abilities is much harder since once they deploy the minion you can’t exactly send it back (yet).  Preventing the site resurrection can be achieved with mapping or pathing a new one.  Another way of preventing minion build up is reducing the deck size or hand size or even just hand content.  I believe only the Shire and Gandalf lacks the ability to play with your opponents cards in hand or deck.  Most discard strategies require a specific deck theme, but a few can be more widely used.  If you play a dwarf, be it ally or companion, packing a greatest kingdom of my people works wonders against Moria and Sauron.  Splashing a dwarf ally and this condition can be achieved in most decks but it’s only successful against 2 cultures so it’s overall versatility is 50%.  The elves have many ways to cause discarding or hand management.  Such possessions as white arrows and Galadriel’s mirror are very useful.  They also have conditions and events which cause discarding, ie. far-seeing eyes, foul creation, ancient enmity etc.  Gondor has really only one way to screw with your opponent and this is by giving them a new hand via change of plans.  This card is not too helpful since it only works during the regroup phase so is really only helpful for double moving.  Overall, denying the shadow minions is more of a theme answer to swarm rather than a generic answer.  Although this theme is quite useful against all cultures so it’s not limited to a single shadow type.<br>
<br>
4) Me and my 8 friends can tackle anything.<br>
A most obvious way of stopping a swarm is by making the required number of minions completely ridiculous.  If you have all 9 companions out, the shadow requires 10 minions.  This means they have to have a all minion hand and be able to draw on minions from other sources.  True this can be a good preventative to swarm but it is highly theme oriented and has severe drawbacks against many decks.  Adding so much twilight to the pool can be devastating if your opponent can use it.  Also, many cards exploit the use of so many companions so again you can feel the pain.  This tactic is really only a benefit of the nine walkers theme and is not suggested as a solution for you deck.  Another way to increase the swarm requirements is to create “ghost” companions, this can be achieved by bringing in allies or having defender +1 companions.  Bringing in allies is quite common, one such dude is Tharin, he does this on his own so it’s only a single card requirement to your deck, but is usually only a one time use.  If your deck is ally stacked then you can use the “bat-signal” and call in your allies, such cards are support of the last homely house, one whom men would follow etc.  Depending on the power of your ally this can be more than just a one shot deal.  Elrond is extremely tough and can win many skirmishes.  But alas this is quite a card intensive combo and really isn’t viable as a generic fix.  It also adds dead cards to most decks if the opponent is unable to really give you the need to use them.  Defender +1 is probably one of the best ways to add “ghost” companions.  Aragorn, ROTN has this ability built in, he’s in many decks so right away this ‘could’ be a generic fix.  But it does depend on whether you require KIE healing or not.  Sam, PP also has this ability and again could be a generic fix.  Now Dwarven, Elven, Gandalf and Gondor cultures all have events which can create defender +X companions.  These cards can be highly useful in preventing swarm and since 4 of 5 cultures have these cards it is a generic fix.  Draw backs to using these can be dead cards against small minion attacks and having a companion take on more than one minion can result in an overwhelmed companion, but at least it’s not Frodo.<br>
<br>
5) Football offensive tackle vs computer nerds.<br>
Well if you’re big enough you can take on more than one minion at a time.  There are numerous ways to increase a companions strength or overwhelming ability.  I’ll just focus on Frodo preventative techniques.  First off, Frodo enters the game with 4 strength (ring + biceps).  Give him sting and he’s up to 6.  This allows him to tackle up to 11 strength with no worries.  Playing some stealths or other strength boosters can get him equal to the likes Aragorn or Gandalf.  Another way is to add mithril-coat, eliminating minion weapon strength.  Minion weapons aren’t seriously common occurrence but subtracting 1 from minion archery is still nice.  Hobbit allies can also help out.  Bounder and Filbert are quite useful for getting out of a skirmish alive.  The final option is to kill all who stand before you before they can get stacked.  You can do this with PATHS power according to his stature.  Add a burden, deal a damage to every minion facing Frodo, if you have enough you can kill everything except the Balrog.  Splashing some Frodo boosters or protection cards is quite common and generic since everyone has to play Frodo.  I should also mention archery as an antidote to swarms.  Archery can’t really be “splashed” into any deck but if it is there, it works well against swarm and non-swarm decks.  Hence it’s extreme popularity.<br>
<br>
Overall there are quite a few ways to prevent swarm but only a few are truly generic.  I’ve found that playing condition removal, some defender +X, and Frodo protection have uses against most shadow types and give some swarm protection.  This usually only adds up to a few cards dedicated, ie. 2 condition removal, 2 +X cards, sting and a bounder, that’s 6 cards and most can be played in any deck.<br>
<br>
I hope I’ve given some insight into how to alleviate the headache of facing a swarm.  You should now be able to laugh at your opponent and say &quot;You and What Army??&quot;<br>
<br>
I hope I didn&#39;t bore you and that my spelling and grammar was up to par. <br>
<br>
Thanks for reading,<br>
Catch-ya-later<br>
